## Example 5 — Real-World: Ice Cream Cone Capacity

An ice cream cone has a radius of 3 cm and a height of 12 cm. A scoop of ice cream is a hemisphere sitting on top with the same radius. What is the total volume of ice cream (cone + hemisphere)?

### Step 1: Volume of the Cone

$$V_{\text{cone}} = \frac{1}{3}\pi(3)^2(12) = \frac{1}{3}\pi(9)(12) = 36\pi \approx 113.10 \text{ cm}^3$$

### Step 2: Volume of the Hemisphere Scoop

$$V_{\text{hemi}} = \frac{2}{3}\pi(3)^3 = \frac{2}{3}\pi(27) = 18\pi \approx 56.55 \text{ cm}^3$$

### Step 3: Total Volume

$$V_{\text{total}} = 36\pi + 18\pi = 54\pi \approx 169.65 \text{ cm}^3$$

✅ Answer: Total ice cream volume is $54\pi \approx$ **169.65 cm³**.

---

## Example 6 — Composite Solid Volume

A grain silo consists of a cylinder with radius 5 m and height 20 m, topped with a cone of the same radius and height 6 m. Find the total volume.

### Step 1: Volume of the Cylinder

$$V_{\text{cyl}} = \pi(5)^2(20) = 500\pi \approx 1570.80 \text{ m}^3$$

### Step 2: Volume of the Cone

$$V_{\text{cone}} = \frac{1}{3}\pi(5)^2(6) = \frac{1}{3}\pi(25)(6) = 50\pi \approx 157.08 \text{ m}^3$$

### Step 3: Total Volume

$$V_{\text{total}} = 500\pi + 50\pi = 550\pi \approx 1727.88 \text{ m}^3$$

### Step 4: Context Check

The conical roof adds about 157 m³, or roughly 10% more capacity to the silo.

✅ Answer: Total volume is $550\pi \approx$ **1727.88 m³**.

